Here's the full migration. Your code has **5 patterns** that must change:

---

## Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into threads. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** with `CancellationToken`.

---

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;

        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)       // ← replaces volatile bool
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token);        // ← must accept token (see below)
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;                                // ← replaces ResetAbort; exit loop
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();                                // ← replaces Thread.Abort

        // Wait up to 5 seconds for the thread to exit cooperatively
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();                              // ← CTS is IDisposable
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

## What changed and why

| Original (.NET Framework) | Migrated (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` | Token unifies the flag and the signaling mechanism |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the cooperative equivalent; the `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No abort to reset — you decide whether to continue or exit the loop |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Signals the token; code must check it voluntarily |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then abort | `_workerThread.Join(5000)` | Waits for cooperative exit instead of force-killing |

---

## Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem()` blocks

Your comment says `GetNextItem()` may block. **A `CancellationToken` cannot interrupt a blocking synchronous call.** You must modify it to respect the token. Common approaches:

```csharp
// Option A: If backed by a BlockingCollection<T>
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token);  // throws OperationCanceledException
}

// Option B: If backed by a WaitHandle / ManualResetEvent
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
        new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });

    if (index == 1)
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();

    return DequeueItem();
}

// Option C: If doing synchronous I/O — switch to async
private async Task<WorkItem> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    return await _reader.ReadAsync(token);
}
```

**If `GetNextItem` calls code you cannot modify**, cancellation will stall until that call returns naturally. In that case, consider moving the work to a child `Process` and using `Process.Kill()`.

---

## Other pitfalls to watch for

1. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it leaks timers/callbacks if you don't. The `IDisposable` implementation above handles this.

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — only catch it at the top-level loop. If `ProcessItem` has sub-methods, let the exception propagate up.

3. **Pass the token through the full call chain** — if `ProcessItem` calls other long-running methods, they all need the token:
   ```csharp
   private void ProcessItem(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
   {
       // check between expensive steps
       DoStepOne(item);
       token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
       DoStepTwo(item);
   }
   ```

4. **Cancellation is not immediate** — it only fires at the next checkpoint. Space `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` calls based on your acceptable shutdown latency.

5. **`RollbackCurrentTransaction` moved** — in the original code, `ResetAbort` let the thread survive and loop again. In the migrated version, cancellation means "shut down," so we `break` after rollback. If you need per-item cancellation (abort one item, continue the loop), use a **linked token per item**:
   ```csharp
   using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
   itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout
   try { ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token); }
   catch (OperationCanceledException) when (itemCts.IsCancellationRequested && !token.IsCancellationRequested)
   {
       RollbackCurrentTransaction();
       // loop continues — only the item was cancelled, not the processor
   }
   ```
